abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., Oct. 31. -- Yale Freshmen made merry at the expense of Andover Academy here to-day, piling up 22 points and blanking the visitors. Potter, Merritt, and Kisler were the Yale stars and Porter and Coates showed the best all-around play for Andover.

abstract: CLEVELAND, Ohio, Nov. 3. -- Early returns indicate a Republican victory in Ohio. abstract: Fordham's football team overwhelmed Georgetown yesterday at the American League Park, winning by the score of 22-0. While the score was onesided it did not carry as much credit to the victors as the total would indicate. It was rather the result of Georgetown's poor playing than Fordham's good field work that enabled the latter to pile up four touchdowns and two goals.

abstract: NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y., Nov. 3. -- Twenty-five floaters from New York invaded New Rochelle this morning, but before they could vote the police learned of their presence and chased them out of town. They put up a fight and several of them were beaten by the police. In the struggle one of them dropped a blackjack. Two were made prisoners and are now in custody of the New Rochelle police charged with vagrancy.

abstract: All records for crowds, even on election night, were broken last night at the various theatres, especially at those in the vicinity of Broadway and Times Square. Long before 8 o'clock long lines of impatient people clamoring for tickets besieged the box offices, and at nearly every playhouse from 100 to 500 people were turned away, and this, after the number entitled to standing room had been stretched to the limit.

abstract: HOT SPRINGS, Va., Nov. 4. -- President-elect Taft and his party are to arrive on Saturday morning. abstract: Down Sixtieth Street toward the East, River ran a red taxicab of the New York Taxicab Company early last evening. On the box were three men. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Nov. 4. -- In the business world to-day there was little talk that did not touch upon the revival of business. Merchants, manufacturers, bankers united in declaring that the Republican victory throughout the country had put an end to apprehension of unfavorable commercial conditions. abstract: CHICAGO, Nov. 19. -- Closely following the transfer of Peter Van Vlissingen to cell in the Joliet Penitentiary to-day, the authorities made the startling discovery that his outstanding forgeries total nearly $2,000,000 instead of the $700,000 he estimated in his confession. This huge loss has been suffered by approximately 100 persons instead of twenty-five, as Van Vlissingen stated.

abstract: WEST POINT, N.Y., Nov. 21. -- In the last game to be played on the home gridiron, the Army defeated Villa Nova here to-day by a score of 25 to 0. The visitors put up a strong defense, but there was no stopping the attack of the Army, and they steadily forged ahead by straight football, twice carrying the ball from the 40-yard mark.

abstract: AMHERST, Mass., Nov. 21. -- Amherst defeated Williams 4 to 0 in a hard-fought contest played on Pratt Field this afternoon. The students massed early in the evening and marched to the Lehigh Valley Railroad station, where they yelled and sang for half an hour.

abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., Nov. 24. -- Edward Harris Coy, full back for two years on the Yale football team, was to-night elected Captain of the eleven for the coming year. His only opponent was Stephen H. Philbin, who has played half back during the past season. After the choice was announced the election was made unanimous, and the members of the team were entertained at dinner by Robert W. Burch, Captain of this year's eleven.

abstract: OSSINING, N.Y., Nov. 28. -- James Lione, a 17-year-old Italian, who lived at 84 North Highland Avenue, was found murdered this morning near the repair shop at the old Croton Aqueduct at Briarcliff. abstract: WASHINGTON, Nov. 29. -- Accompanied by a small suite Queen Liliuokalani arrived in Washington to-day prepared to plead with Congress for the grant of $200,000 with which to live gracefully, as royalty should, the few years remaining to her.
